[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "THE CONSECRATION COMPLETED BY ADDITIONAL SACRIFICES",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(2Chronicles 29:31-36).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 29:31-36",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(31) Answered and said.—See 1Chronicles 12:17. The phrase is used as we should use it in Exodus 4:1; 2Kings 7:13.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(31) ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Answered and said.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 12:17",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The phrase is used as we should use it in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Exodus 4:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Kings 7:13",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Ye have consecrated . . .—Literally, ye have filled your hand for Jehovah, a phrase used of the consecration of priests (Leviticus 7:37). Here it is addressed to the whole assembly, as the following words prove (unless the text be unsound). The congregation, as well as the sacerdotal order, had consecrated themselves anew to Jehovah, by their presence and participation in the previous solemnities. Others suppose that these words are spoken to the priests only, and that then the king turns to the congregation with the words “Come near,” &c. (There should be a semicolon after “the Lord.”)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Ye have consecrated . . .",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Literally, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "ye have filled your hand for Jehovah,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " a phrase used of the consecration of priests (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 7:37",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "). Here it is addressed to the whole assembly, as the following words prove (unless the text be unsound). The congregation, as well as the sacerdotal order, had consecrated themselves anew to Jehovah, by their presence and participation in the previous solemnities. Others suppose that these words are spoken to the priests only, and that then the king turns to the congregation with the words “Come near,” &c. (There should be a semicolon after “the Lord.”)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Sacrifices and thank offerings (zebahîn we thôdôth).—The first word means “thank-offerings” ( = zébahîm shelamîm); the second, a peculiar species of thank-offering, apparently accompanied by a special kind of psalms called tôdôth (“thanksgivings”). “Sacrifices and thank-offerings” therefore means “sacrifices, that is, thank-offerings.” (See Leviticus 7:12; Leviticus 7:16, for the three kinds of thank-offerings.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Sacrifices and thank offerings ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "zebahîn we thôdôth",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ")",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The first word means ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "“",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "thank-offerings” ( = ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "zébahîm shelamîm",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ")",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": ";",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " the second, a peculiar species of thank-offering, apparently accompanied by a special kind of psalms called ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "tôdôth",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (“thanksgivings”). “Sacrifices ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "and",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " thank-offerings” therefore means “sacrifices, that is, thank-offerings.” (See ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 7:12",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 7:16",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", for the three kinds of thank-offerings.)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "As many as were of a free heart.—Literally, Every free-hearted one (1Chronicles 29:6; 1Chronicles 29:9).",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "As many as were of a free heart.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Literally, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Every free-hearted one",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " (",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 29:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 29:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ").",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Burnt offerings were a token of greater self-denial and disinterestedness than thank-offerings, because they were wholly consumed on the altar, whereas the worshippers feasted upon the latter.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Burnt offerings",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " were a token of greater self-denial and disinterestedness than thank-offerings, because they were wholly consumed on the altar, whereas the worshippers feasted upon the latter.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 29:31",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Chronicles 29:31",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Now ye have consecrated yourselves to the Lord — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Have both made an atonement, and made a covenant by sacrifice; are solemnly reconciled and engaged to him; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "come near and bring sacrifices — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Our covenant with God must be pursued and improved in communion with him. Having consecrated ourselves in the first place to the Lord, we must bring the sacrifices of prayer, and praise, and alms, to his house. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "As many as were of a free heart brought burnt-offerings — ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Wherein there was more generosity than in the other sacrifices, because they were wholly burned and offered to God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "29:20-36 As soon as Hezekiah heard that the temple was ready, he lost no time. Atonement must be made for the sins of the last reign. It was not enough to lament and forsake those sins; they brought a sin-offering. Our repentance and reformation will not obtain pardon but in and through Christ, who was made sin, that is, a sin-offering for us. While the offerings were on the altar, the Levites sang. Sorrow for sin must not prevent us from praising God. The king and the congregation gave their consent to all that was done. It is not enough for us to be where God is worshipped, if we do not ourselves worship with the heart. And we should offer up our spiritual sacrifices of praise and thanksgiving, and devote ourselves and all we have, as sacrifices, acceptable to the Father only through the Redeemer.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Hezekiah addresses, not the priests, but the congregation: \"Now that by the atoning sacrifice which has been offered for you, you are consecrated once more to be a holy people to the Lord, approach with confidence and offer your free-will offerings as of old.\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Burnt offerings - The term thus translated is applied especially to those victims which were to be wholly consumed upon the altar. In the \"sacrifices,\" or peace offerings generally, and the \"thank offerings\" - a particular kind of peace offering Leviticus 7:12) - the greater part of the victim belonged to, and was consumed by, the worshipper. Hence, to offer \"burnt offerings,\" was indicative of a \"free heart.\" ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Burnt offerings - The term thus translated is applied especially to those victims which were to be wholly consumed upon the altar. In the \"sacrifices,\" or peace offerings generally, and the \"thank offerings\" - a particular kind of peace offering ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Leviticus 7:12",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ") - the greater part of the victim belonged to, and was consumed by, the worshipper. Hence, to offer \"burnt offerings,\" was indicative of a \"free heart.\" ",
            "children": []
